<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
    <title>Student Report</title>
    <style>
      table {
        border-collapse: collapse;
        margin: 40px auto;
        font-size: 1.2rem;
      }
      th,
      td {
        border: 2px solid #222;
        padding: 12px 24px;
        text-align: center;
      }
      .red {
        color: red;
      }
      h1 {
        text-align: center;
        margin-top: 40px;
        font-size: 2.5rem;
      }
    </style>
  </head>
  <body>
    <h1>Student Report</h1>
    <table>
      <tr>
        <th>Name</th>
        <th>Math</th>
        <th>Science</th>
        <th>English</th>
      </tr>
      <% students.forEach(student => { %>
      <tr>
        <td><%= student.name %></td>
        <td class="<%= student.marks.math < 70 ? 'red' : '' %>">
          <%= student.marks.math %>
        </td>
        <td class="<%= student.marks.science < 70 ? 'red' : '' %>">
          <%= student.marks.science %>
        </td>
        <td class="<%= student.marks.english < 70 ? 'red' : '' %>">
          <%= student.marks.english %>
        </td>
      </tr>
      <% }) %>
    </table>
  </body>
</html>


<!-- In <td> tag, we use this EJS code inside the "class" attribute so that we can conditionally apply a CSS class to the table cell based on the student's marks.

- If `student.marks.math < 70` is true, the class "red" is added, making the text red (using your CSS).
- If the marks are 70 or above, the class is empty, so the cell uses the default color.

By putting the EJS code inside the `class` attribute, you control the cell's appearance dynamically, based on the data. This is a common way to highlight or style table cells conditionally in EJS templates. -->